Classification accuracy for the SCWT WR raw was 0.775.
When assessing the accuracy for distinguishing amongst valid groups (ADHD vs other psychological conditions vs no diagnosis), no IIV-I or IIV-D measure exhibited acceptable classification accuracy (all AUCs < 0.70)..{#13971}
The embedded validity indicators from the Stroop Color and Word Test were effective in determining validity status. Word Reading and Color Naming trials demonstrated acceptable classification accuracy (AUCs 0.750–0.794), with optimal cut scores of WR raw ≤75 (54% sensitivity, 89-90% specificity), WR T score ≤28 (54% sensitivity, 87-88% specificity), CN raw ≤57 (42% sensitivity, 90% specificity), and CN T score ≤30 (40% sensitivity, 90% specificity).{#447}
The memory-based RAVLT and BVMT-R PVTs were able to accurately identify invalid neuropsychological test performance among adults undergoing evaluation for ADHD, regardless of whether diagnostic criteria for ADHD were met.{#5528}
RDS distinguished adults feigning ADHD from genuine responders with 35% sensitivity and 93% specificity. RDWM distinguished adults feigning ADHD from genuine responders with 56% sensitivity and 86% specificity. RDS-R distinguished adults feigning ADHD from genuine responders with 48% sensitivity and 85% specificity. ACSS distinguished adults feigning ADHD from genuine responders with 46% sensitivity and 87% specificity.{#11175}
Intra-invariability measures ISD, CoV, HRT SD, HRT SD/HRT, VAR, and VAR/HRT significantly differed between valid and invalid groups with the Invalid group having higher IIV values than all other groups.{#13971} 
Combining indicators into a multivariate model significantly improved classification accuracy, explaining up to 36% of the variance in validity status (Stroop Color and Word Test, Trail Making Test, Verbal Fluency Test, and Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale-Fourth Edition) with AUC 0.86.{#263}
A machine learning supported model achieved an AUC of 0.85 distinguishing credible vs probable noncredible reporting (CI 0.82, 0.87).{#11007}
Overreporting cut-scores identified for each of the BAARS-IV scales demonstrated acceptable classification accuracy or better.  The Current Total and Current Sluggish Cognitive Tempo scales captured nonredundant aspects of symptom validity, and using them together increased sensitivity to 57% while maintaining ≥90% specificity.{#11008}
CPT-3 embedded validity indicators showed unacceptably high false-positive rates around 11.7%; WAIS-IV Letter-Number Sequencing embedded validity indicators showed false-positive rates of 10.8%–11.1%; SCWT embedded validity indicators had variable false-positive rates, ranging from 4.0% to 12.5%, with higher rates for standardized scores; Trail Making Test embedded indicators showed a wide range of false-positive rates, with Trail B raw score cutoff yielding the highest at 18.2%; Lexical and Semantic Fluency embedded indicators showed the highest false-positive rate for raw lexical fluency (17.4%) and a low rate for standardized scores (2.8%); RAVLT embedded indicator showed a false-positive rate of 9.5%.{#11009}
